    # Que 1: Name any five plots that we can plot using the Seaborn library. Also, state the uses of each plot.
    ​
    1. Scatter Plot: A scatter plot is a two-dimensional plot that uses dots to represent data points. It is used to visualize the relationship between two variables, and can be useful in identifying patterns or trends. Seaborn provides various options to customize the scatter plot such as color-coding data based on another variable, adding regression lines, and adjusting marker size.
    ​
    2. Line Plot: A line plot is a plot in which data points are connected by lines. It is used to visualize trends in data over time or to show the relationship between two variables. Seaborn provides various options to customize the line plot such as changing line styles, adding markers at data points, and adding shaded regions to indicate confidence intervals.
    ​
    3. Histogram: A histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution of a dataset. It displays the frequency distribution of a set of continuous data by dividing the data into intervals called bins and counting the number of observations that fall into each bin. Seaborn provides options to adjust the number of bins, normalize the histogram, and overlay a kernel density estimate.
    ​
    4. Bar Plot: A bar plot is a plot that represents categorical data with rectangular bars. It is used to compare the values of different categories. Seaborn provides options to customize the bar plot such as changing the color of bars, adding error bars, and stacking bars to show the total value.
    ​
    5. Heatmap: A heatmap is a plot that shows the relationship between two variables by displaying the values as colors in a two-dimensional grid. It is used to identify patterns and relationships in large datasets. Seaborn provides options to customize the heatmap such as changing the color map, adjusting the grid size, and adding annotations.

    Que 1: Name any five plots that we can plot using the Seaborn library. Also, state the uses of each plot.¶

    1. Scatter Plot: A scatter plot is a two-dimensional plot that uses dots to represent data points. It is used to visualize the relationship between two variables, and can be useful in identifying patterns or trends. Seaborn provides various options to customize the scatter plot such as color-coding data based on another variable, adding regression lines, and adjusting marker size.

    2. Line Plot: A line plot is a plot in which data points are connected by lines. It is used to visualize trends in data over time or to show the relationship between two variables. Seaborn provides various options to customize the line plot such as changing line styles, adding markers at data points, and adding shaded regions to indicate confidence intervals.

    3. Histogram: A histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution of a dataset. It displays the frequency distribution of a set of continuous data by dividing the data into intervals called bins and counting the number of observations that fall into each bin. Seaborn provides options to adjust the number of bins, normalize the histogram, and overlay a kernel density estimate.

    4. Bar Plot: A bar plot is a plot that represents categorical data with rectangular bars. It is used to compare the values of different categories. Seaborn provides options to customize the bar plot such as changing the color of bars, adding error bars, and stacking bars to show the total value.

    5. Heatmap: A heatmap is a plot that shows the relationship between two variables by displaying the values as colors in a two-dimensional grid. It is used to identify patterns and relationships in large datasets. Seaborn provides options to customize the heatmap such as changing the color map, adjusting the grid size, and adding annotations.
